content:
Here is a Julia function that performs the required functionality:
```julia
using Dates

function timezone_bumper(dt::DateTime; bump::Int = 3)
    # Increase date time by bump hours
    return dt + Hour(bump)
end

# Test function
@testset "Testing timezone_bumper" begin
    @test isequal(timezone_bumper(DateTime("2021-09-15T08:00:00")), DateTime("2021-09-15T11:00:00"))
    @test_throws ErrorException timezone_bumper(Date("2021-09-15", "yyyy-mm-dd"))
end
```
This function takes a DateTime object as input and returns the same DateTime object, increased by `bump` hours. If a Date object is passed instead, it throws an error. 

Please note that the "2021-09-15T08:00:00" format is used for testing purposes where "T" represents the time separator between date and time.
